{
  "texts": [
    "Here, we analyze encoding of coarser positions by choosing large position bins across the whole track (Fig. 6C, D).",
    "We consider different bin sizes to characterize at which scale the merging of examples into concepts occurs.",
    "When we again compute the average difference in sparsity-corrected position information per spike between sparse and dense theta phases, we find that dense phases are the most preferentially informative at the coarsest scales (Fig. 6E).",
    "CA1 place cells also exhibit this property (Supplementary Fig. 6B).",
    "Crucially, differences between sparse and dense phases are not seen in shuffled data, which supports the validity of our analysis methods (Fig. 6F)."
  ]
}